Careers in Academic Administration.

Villa-Komaroff L(1).

Author information:
(1)Intersections SBD, Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts 02467.

Academic administration can be an extension of an academic career at the bench 
or it can run parallel to a career of discovery. To be an academic administrator 
at the executive level in a college or university generally requires advancement 
through the academic ranks to the professorial level. These positions include 
department chair, dean of a college, head of a center or institute, provost, 
senior research officer, and university or college president. Positions that can 
begin immediately after attaining a PhD or after a postdoctoral position include 
some assistant dean roles and positions in technology transfer, grants 
management, and laboratory management, among many others. Many of the skills 
developed during the pursuit of an advanced degree in the life sciences are 
directly applicable to these jobs. All require problem solving, critical 
thinking, collaboration, and the ability to communicate clearly.

